column168: On 2/1/17, a Schneider Bulk Carriers intermodal 407 tank was found leaking at the Schneider Bulk facility in Reserve, LA.  The container was loaded with 20203 kilograms of UN3082 Tomadol 23-5 surfactant. It appeared as if the release stemmed from a faulty weld seam on the underside of the tank. The leaking tank released approximately 1 gallon of material to a compact soil and gravel parking lot. No drains or waterways were impacted by the release.  Upon discovery of the release the tank was moved to containment area by Schneider Bulk personnel in order to transfer the material to a new tank.  An environmental contractor was dispatched to respond to the release and excavate any impacted soil.  A 40' stretch of impacted gravel and soil was hand excavated and all free material recovered. The contractors generated (1) 55 gallon steel drum of waste which was taken offsite for disposal.  Schneider Bulk personnel transferred the material into a new tank without incident.

column168: I, John Vergis, Environmental Officer for Wheeling and Lake Erie Railway, was contacted about a possible leaking rail car in Brewster Yard involving tank car CBTX 741415. This car was noticed to have an odor coming from it by the yard switch crew. They notified the Brewster Yardmaster, who then notified myself. I was unable to respond to the incident. I contacted Sunpro Environmental Services to respond to the possible leak. When they arrived and investigated, they used a 5 gas meter to determine that the odors were coming from around the manway lid. They determined the vapor leak was caused by loose manway bolts. They tightened all the swing bolts, and used their 5 gas meter to determine the vapor leak had stopped. The car was then released for service.
column169: Better car securement procedures need to be followed.

column168: A vehicle operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc was en route from the shipper’s location to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at a 10 day transfer facility for the purpose of consolidating less than truck load quantities on a single transport vehicle for continued transportation. During the transfer operation, it was discovered that approximately 5 ounces of material had  escaped from a pinhole leak that had developed in the container. Facility personnel assembled a response team who proceeded to place the compromised  container into a suitable salvage drum. Once complete, the container was secured and was placed onto the trailer for continued transportation.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of damage or leaking was observed. Drivers will continue to inspect each container prior to receiving, as well during staging period and will take all appropriate actions should a container show evidence of reduced structural integrity. In addition, the shipper has been advised of the situation and have been asked to inspect all containers used for the transport of waste materials to insure they meet all required specifications.

On February 10, 2017, the carrier (Seaboard Marine) was advised by the shipper (Price Smart Inc) that undeclared hazardous materials were stowed inside container SMLU 782224-9 (UN1993). The container was loaded on the Vessel Hansa Augsburg V-39 at the time we (Seaboard Marine) received notice that undeclared hazardous cargoes had been loaded.  Upon receiving notice from the shipper we immediately placed a HOLD on the container and advised Capt of the Vessel. The shipper was asked to provide the proper documentation describing all the hazardous materials inside of the container. On February 12, 2017, upon receipt, review and acceptance of the shipping papers, the Capt. reported that unit will be placarded at the Port of Discharge (BQA) since container cannot be accessed in its current stowed position. On February 14, the container was placarded accordingly and subsequently released for transportation.

On 2/7/2017, a CTL Distribution DOT407 tanker (C21141) was offloading 20460 pounds of UN1866 vinyl ester resin at a Spectra Composites facility in Jamestown, SC.  During the offloading process a hose leading from the CTL Distribution tanker to a tank within the facility ruptured near the outlet valve of the tanker.  The ruptured hose released approximately 10 gallons of material before the tankers valve could be closed.  The release impacted the side of the building, tanker and an area of soil and gravel beneath the tanker.  No drains or waterways were impacted by the release. There were no injuries or exposures due to the release.  An environmental contractor was dispatched to clean the impacted areas.  The environmental contractor hand excavated an approximate 8'x10' area of impacted soil and containerized the impacted soil into 55 gallon steel drums.  The side of the building and tanker were cleaned off with an acetone solution and rags.  The impacted rags and debris were containerized in 55 gallon steel drums as well.  All free product was recovered and in total, 2 55 gallon steel drums of waste were generated. The waste was staged on site pending profiling and proper disposal.  The CTL Distribution tanker secured a new hose on the tanker and the transfer was completed without further incident.
DONNED FULL PPE AND RESPONDED TO CALL. FOLLOWED THE DECISION TREE AND APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET. CLEANED UP THE SPILL AND REMOVED THE PACKAGE.

column168: On 2/15/17, a 55 gallon steel drum of UN1866 Adcote was punctured by a fork lift blade while unloading a trailer at the XPO Logistics facility in King of Prussia, PA. The damaged drum released approximately 30 gallons of material to the trailer floor and parking lot. No soils, drains or waterways were impacted by the release. An environmental contractor was dispatched to respond to the release and clean the impacted areas. The environmental contractors utilized granular absorbents and a solvent solution to clean the trailer floor and parking lot. All impacted absorbents were containerized into (2) 55 gallon steel drums and labeled as hazardous waste. The damaged drum and remaining product were overpacked into an 85 gallon steel drum and labeled as hazardous waste. All three drums were staged on site for XPO personnel to manage.

column168: TOTX 1027 was identified as possibly releasing by the BNSF Railway Custer Service Department in Parachute, CO on February 1 , 2017. The cause of the release was identified by BNSF Hazmat Manger, Ryan Risdon as a defect in one of the two Pressure Relief Devices on the car.  The Pressure Relief Device Internal Spring at some point became disengaged from the rod itself.  Ryan Risdon secured the Pressure Relief Device Rod/Retainer Cap  with the use of a pulley/gear puller to ensure the rod is not moving freely and the retainer cap stays in place.      OTMA1 has been requested by the shipper to move this car back into their plant.

column168: At 2158 hours, on 2/17/2017, the Brewster yard switch crew reported an odor coming from tank car TILX 304088. I, John Vergis, Environmental Officer for WLE was contacted by the Brewster Yardmaster to investigate this leak. When I arrived, I was able to hear the sound of pressure being released from on top of the car. When I investigated, I found that the vapor valve was leaking through the plug. The valve handle and valve plug was loose. I tightened the valve handle and the leak stopped. I then tightened the valve plug. After this leak had stopped, I still noticed the sound of pressure being released. I found that the liquid valve on the B end of the car was also leaking. The valve handle and plug was loose in this valve also. I tightened the valve handle and the leak stopped. I also tightened the valve plug. After this, all leaks were stopped. I then released the car for service. Old seal number 0076728 was removed from the protective housing, and new seal number 971725 was applied.
column169: Better car securement procedures need to be followed.

column168: Unit was northbound on US183 enroute to Lampasas, Texas for load delivery.  Unit drifted off right side of roadway.  Unit traveled along inclined shoulder and rolled.  Unit came to rest on left side on private property.  The integrity of the cargo tank was not compromised.  Upon arrival of first responders, clamping devices were applied to the manhole covers to prevent product seepage from the manhole covers.  "Microblaze" absorbent was applied to ground surface to absorb any seepage.  A recovery cargo tank motor vehicle was positioned near the rollover unit.  Access holes were drilled into the rolled unit and a product hose was positioned between the rolled unit and the recovery unit.  Product pump off operation was initiated.  The product pump off operation took approximately 4 hours.  The pump off operation was performed by Coastal employees and environmental response company employees.  During the pump off operation, product seeped through defective hose equipment that was being used during the pump off.  Math calculations of recovered product indicate that less than 200 gallons of product leaked through the defective hose during the 4 hour pump off time period.
column169: The Coastal employees have been reminded that they hold "stop work authority" when unsafe conditions are encountered.  The Coastal employees have been instructed that they will not use defective hose equipment when conducting a pump off operation.

column168: ON 2/2/2017, THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE INSPECTED RAIL CARS LOCATED IN THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCS) SHREVEPORT, LA YARD. DURING THE INSPECTION GATX  71661, A RESIDUE LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS TANK CAR, WAS FOUND LEAKING FROM THE A END LIQUID VALVE AND SECONDARY CLOSURE PLUG. KCS ENVIRONMENTAL AND HAZMAT DISPATCHED A HAZMAT RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO INVESTIGATE AND SECURE THE PACKAGE. UPON ARRIVAL, THE LEAK WAS STOPPED BY CLOSING THE VALVE, REMOVING THE PLUG. CLEANING THREADS AND APPLYING TEFLON TAPE, AND REAPPLYING PLUG TOOL TIGHT. ONCE COMPLETE, THE TANK CAR WAS RELEASED BACK INTO TRANSPORTATION. FILE NOTE: ITEM 19-THE QUANTITY RELEASE WAS ESTIMATED BASED ON THE BEST INFORMATION AVAILABLE AT THE TIME OF FILING. THIS SHIPMENT WAS OFFERED AS A "BULK" SHIPMENT AKA ONE CAR LOAD. THEREFORE THE EXACT AMOUNT OFFERED IN THIS PACKAGE IS NOT KNOWN TO THE CARRIER. THE CARRIER DOES NOT HAVE ACCESS TO MASS BALANCE DATA WHICH CAN EXACTLY QUANTITY THIS VALUE.
column169: THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCSR) NOTIFED SHIPPER OF THIS RELEASE. NON ACCIDENTAL RELEASES (NAR) CAN BE DEVASTATING ON SEVERAL DIFFERENT LEVELS. THEY CAN CAUSE PERSONAL INJURY, ENVIRONMENTAL DAMAGE, DISRPUT RAIL YARDS, ADJANCENT FACILITIES AND COMMUNITIES AND SNARL TRAIN OPERATIONS FOR UNDREDS OF MILES AND BOTH DIRECTIONS. NARS ARE TROUBLESOME TO ALL BECAUSE THEY ARE, BY AND LARGE PREVENTABLE. FOR NON ACCIDENT RELEASE (AKA PACKAGE CLOSURE ISSUES SUCH AS THIS), THE SHIPPER IS REQUESTED TO CONDUCT A ROOT CASUED INVESTIGATION TO DETERMINE THE CAUSES OF RELEASE AND TO THEM FACILITATE CORRECTIVE ACTION TO PREVENT RECURRENCE. IT IS REQUEST THAT THE SHIPPER SHARE THEIR FINDINGS WITH KCS (PLEASE DIRECT YOUR ROOT CASUE INVESTIGATION RESULTS AND CORRECTIVE ACTIONS TO STEVE MCNEALY, KCS RAILWAY PO BOX 219335, KANSAS CITY MO 64121. THE SHIPPER CAN REFERENEC HTTP:// NAR.AAR.COM FOR HELP UNDERSTANIDNG AND PREVENTING NARS

column168: This incident pertains to a release of a UN1268 Petroleum Distillates. There was (1) - 330 gallon metal tote found leaking inside the trailer. The tote appears to have a defective seal on the cap at the tote of the tote. Approximately 1 quart of material released to the trailer floor. No soils, drains, or waterways were impacted. XPO Logistics personnel conducted cleanup operations for this release. The tote was staged on site pending the shippers disposition.

The drum was being transferred from a Veolia truck to a van for shipment to the receiving facility at a 10-Day transfer facility located in Bartow, Fl.  An operator at the 10-Day yard was in the process of transferring the drum utilizing a forklift and drum grabber attachment.  As the drum was picked up, the operator noticed the drum was leaking from the bottom.  The operator immediately notified the Veolia employee who was supervising the transfer and together they flipped the drum over to prevent further spillage.  They over-packed the drum into a 851A2 salvage drum.  The spilled material was cleaned up utilizing oil dry and packed into another drum.  Approximately 3-4 gallons of liquid was spilled from the drum.  Upon visible inspection of the bottom of the drum, there was visible rust formation and a split in the bottom seam.  There were no visible signs of rust or damage on any other part of the drum.  It is believed the failure of the drum was due to a combination of age and corrosion stress on the drum.
column169: The Gulf Coast Branch of Veolia will institute a new policy regarding the handling of drums from Automotive type shops. In future pickups, any drums that are over 2 years old and/or have not been stored inside will be required to be over-packed into a salvage drum prior to shipment.

column168: On February 22, 2017, at 15:30 hours, personnel in the CSXT Hopewell Yard discovered SHPX 210300, a (loaded) tank car of Molten Sulfur, leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and (Duane Abbott - Chemtrade, VA DEM HMVA  and NRC. were notified.  (CHEMTREC Report #2017-0222-00220 ). HEPACO, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the man way gasket was worn and an excessive amount of build up existed around the nozzle. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Duane Abbott PH#419-913-2766  . Contractor personnel replaced the defective gasket and secured the man way. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1 is not required.    Cause Code:137 - Manway / 517 - Improper Preparation for Transportation  NARRI:

column168: On 2/27/17, a 4 gallon poly pail of UN3109 Microtox was found leaking on a trailer at the XPO Logistics facility in Greencastle, PA.  It was apparent that the pail had been punctured by a nail from the pallet on which it was loaded. The damaged pail released approximately 4 gallons of material to the trailer floor and parking lot. No soils, drains or waterways were impacted by the release.  An environmental contractor was dispatched to clean the release. All released material was recovered with the use of granular absorbents and the damaged pail and impacted absorbents were containerized into a 55 gallon poly drum.  The 55 gallon poly drum was labeled as hazardous waste and staged on site for XPO Logistics personnel to manage.
I RESPONDED IN FULL PPE, FOLLOWED BY RESPONDING WITH SPILL CART AND ALSO FOLLOWING THE PROPER PROCEDURES IN MY DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET.

column168: During a routine inspection from the FRA Hazmat Inspector, car  CRPX 986030 was found to have the B end liquid valve leaking through the valve seat.  The inspector called myself, John Vergis Environmental Officer for Wheeling and Lake Erie Railway to look at the car.  When I arrived and investigated I found that the valve handle was not closed tightly causing the leak.  I tightened the valve handle and the leak stopped.  I then tightened the loose valve plug.  The car was then released for service.
column169: Better car securement procedures need followed.

column168: The shipment: was found leaking in the sort. Upon opening the box we found two - onegallon metal paint cans and two - one liter metal paint cans. Each of the fourmetal cans had friction lids that require plastic ring locks for positive closureunder 49CFR 173.27(d). The cans in this shipment had can clips that will not meetthe 75kPa internal pressure test required for air transport. The friction lidsseparated from the can allowing the spill to occur. The freight is on a hold for anFAA inspection. Hazmat Manager Stan Satchell with the MEM SECFO was notifiedelectronically.

column168: While unloading the route truck 2 damaged IBC's were noted. The first had a crack in the body neat the top cap on the seam and produced no release. The second was leaking from the lower valve. The leak was minor, less than 1 liquid pint of material was released into containment. After donning proper PPE the leak was prevented from expanding. A third party vendor was notified and responded transferring both damaged toted into new, undamaged containers. The damaged containers were dismantled , placed into appropriate containers and disposed of properly. Released material was cleaned up and also properly disposed of.

column168: A Norfolk Southern employee reported an odor of gas near several tank cars. The employee reported they felt ill and requested medical attention. The tank cars in the area included UTLX954267 containing the residue and 4 residue tanks cars of asphalt.  The area was inspected by HEPACO, an emergency response contractor for Norfolk Southern. During the inspection and air monitoring tank car UTLX954267 was found with a small vapor leak from the B-end liquid valve plug. The valve was found partially open and the closure plug was not completely tight. The valve was closed and the plug tightened to stop the leak. During the inspection tank car CBTX727921 containing the residue of asphalt was found with a partially open manway and the odor of asphalt present.  (NARRI - 117)

column168: A LEAK FROM A RAILCAR TRANSPORTING LEAD CARBONATE WAS OBSERVED ON FEBRUARY 6, 2017 AT APPROXIMATELY 12:30PM AT THE RTK GARFIELD RAIL YARD, NEAREST ADDRESS RTK TRAILING FACILITY 11984 WEST HIGHWAY 202. RTK RAIL ROAD RECORDS INDICATE THE RAIL CAR LEFT THE RTK REFINERY, 1500 WEST 2100 SOUTH MAGNA, UTAH, AND TRAVELED DIRECTLY TO GARFIELD RAIL YARD.THE MATERIAL RELEASED IS A SOLID WITH A CONSISTENCY OF A THICK MUD. SMALL PLIES, 4-18 INCHES HIGH, AND 12-18 INCHES IN DIAMETER, AND SPLASH OF LEAD CARBONATE WERE OBSERVED WHERE THE RAIL CAR RESTED AT THE REFINERY AND GARFIELD RAIL YARD.     THE RELEASE RESULTED FROM A ROUGHLY 2" CRACK IN A RUBBER PIPE CAP BENEATH THE RAIL CAR. THE PIPING WAS TEMPORARILY REPAIRED AROUND 2:00 PM AND THE RAIL CAR WAS RETURNED TO A CONTAINMENT AREA AT THE REFINERY AROUND 4:00 PM. APPROXIMATELY 1,200 LBS.+/- 50% OF LEAD CARBONATE WAS RELEASED. THIS ESTIMATION IS BASED ON RECORDED WEIGHTS FOR THE CAR WHEN IT LEFT THE REFINERY AND WHEN IT WAS TRANSFERRED TO CONTAINMENT: THE RAIL CAR WEIGHED 261,800 LBS. BEFORE THE RELEASE AND 260,600 LBS. AFTER THE RELEASE AND REPAIR.     THE RELEASE CLEAN-UP INVOLVED REMOVING THE PILES AND SPLASHES, ALONG WITH UNDERLYING RAIL BALLAST AND ROCK WITHIN THE RTK GARFIELD RAIL YARD, AND THE RTK REFINERY RAIL YARD. THE RAIL LINE BETWEEN THE YARD AND THE REFINERY WAS VISUALLY INSPECTED WITH NO PILES OR SIGNIFICANT SPLASHING OBSERVED. OVER 3,000 POUNDS OF MATERIALS WERE REMOVED DURING THE CLEAN-UP VISUAL INSPECTION AFTER CLEAN UP IDENTIFIED ONLY MINOR STAINING ON RAIL AND TIMBERS, CONFIRMING REMOVAL.
column169: REPAIRS TO THE CAR INCLUDED INSERTION OF FOAM INSULATION TO THE PIPE AND A REPLACEMENT CAP. THE CAR THEN RETURNED TO SERVICE UPON CONFIRMATION OF NO FURTHER LEAKS. ONCE RETURNED TO RTKC, THE CAR WILL UNDERGO A COMPLETE INTERNAL VISUAL INSPECTION AND ADDITIONAL REPAIRS, IF ANY, WILL BE PERFORMED.    AFTER THE INCIDENT, THE COMPANY VISUALLY INSPECTED ITS FLEET OF LEASED RAILCARS USED FOR SHIPMENT OF LEAD CARBONATE. THE CARS APPEARED TO BE IN GOOD CONDITION AND DID NOT EXHIBIT SIGNS OF SIMILAR FAILURE. THE COMPANY IS ALSO ENHANCING ITS PRE-LOADING INSPECTIONS BY IMPLEMENTING A PRE-LOADING CHECKLIST TO STANDARDIZE PRE-LOADING INSPECTIONS.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE TRAVELING, A VEHICLE ROLLOVER RESULTED IN THE LOSS OF APPROXIMATELY 7,300 GALLONS OF GASOLINE. THE FREE PRODUCT RELEASED TO THE ASPHALT ROADWAY, ADJACENT DRAINAGE DITCH, AND EVENTUALLY LEADING TO A NEARBY RETENTION POND. LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT, POLICE DEPARTMENT, AND COUNTY OFFICIALS RESPONDED TO ASSESS THE SITE. FIRST CALL ENVIRONMENTAL WAS DISPATCHED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP. UPON ARRIVAL, FIRST CALL ENVIRONMENTAL SECURED THE AREA WITH THE APPLICATION OF ABSORBENT BOOM, A VACUUM TRUCK WAS UTILIZED TO RECOVER FREE LIQUIDS, AND AREA WAS MARKED FOR PENDING EXCAVATION. USEPA RESPONDED TO ASSESS AND NCDENR WAS UPDATED ON SITE PROGRESS. DAILY SITE MONITORING, BOOM MAINTENANCE, AND FREE LIQUID RECOVERY WERE PERFORMED. ONCE MARKOUTS AND UTILITIES WERE LOCATED, EXCAVATION ACTIVITIES WERE PERFORMED ON SITE. FIRST CALL ENVIRONMENTAL RECOVERED THE CONTAMINATED SOIL, PULLED ANALYTICAL SAMPLES, AND RESTORED SITE TO PREEXISTING CONDITION. DISPOSAL WAS COORDINATED IN ACCORDANCE WITH LOCAL, STATE, AND FEDERAL REGULATIONS. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 0220, ON FEBRUARY 24, 2017, RESPONDER WAS DISPATCHED TO PD-9, DOOR 61 FOR A NOXIOUS SMELL INSIDE THE TRAILER. RESPONDER ARRIVED AT THE LOCATION WITH THE SPILL CART AND WEARING ALL APPROPRIATE PPE. A 15' PERIMETER WAS ESTABLISHED. UPON INSPECTION OF THE TRAILER, THERE WAS A STRONG NOXIOUS ODOR PRESENT, BUT NO LEAKER OR WET BOX WAS LOCATED. OUT OF PRECAUTION, THE ONLY VISIBLE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS PACKAGE WAS REMOVED FROM THE TRAILER. IT WAS CONTAINERIZED AND TAKEN TO THE DAMAGE CAGE FOR INSPECTION AND POSSIBLE PROCESSING. UPON INSPECTION, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT ONE OF THE CONTAINERS IN THE PACKAGE WAS LEAKING.
column169: IT APPEARS THAT THIS PACKAGE WAS DROPPED. THERE WAS NO VISIBLE DAMAGE TO THE OUTSIDE BOX, BUT ONE OF THE CONTAINERS INSIDE THE BOX WAS BENT IN ON ITSELF ENOUGH TO CAUSE A SMALL HOLE. THERE WAS VERY LITTLE PACKAGING MATERIAL WHICH ALSO MAY HAVE CONTRIBUTED TO DAMAGING THE CAN. TO PREVENT THIS, BETTER UNLOADING TECHNIQUES AND PACKAGE HANDLING TECHNIQUES SHOULD BE TAUGHT AND MONITORED BY MANAGEMENT. ALSO, ADEQUATE PACKAGING BY THE SHIPPER MAY HAVE PREVENTED CANS FROM BECOMING DAMAGED.

column168: Event/Claim # 63643     Consignee employee was pressurizing the trailer in preparation to unload..  As the CTMV was being pressurized, the consignee employee noticed product was leaking from the hose where it connects on top of the CTMV..  The consignee employee immediately stopped the unloading process when he noticed the leak..     It was discovered that the gasket was worn out causing the product to leak..      The release lasted less than 2 minutes..  Once the product that had been in the hose finished leaking out, the release stopped..      A QC employee was called to replace the worn out gasket with a new gasket..       The product that spilled onto the ground in the containment area was rinsed with a water hose by a consignee employee into a pit..

THE SHIPMENT HAD ARRIVED BY TRUCK FROM LUFTHANSA DETROIT. THE PACKAGES WERE INSPECTED BY LUFTHANSA DETROIT AND LUFTHANSA ORD. WHILE THE CARGO WAS BEING STAGED FOR LOADING ONTO A ULD ,A SMALL AMOUNT OF LEAKAGE WAS NOTICED COMING FROM THE BOTTOM OF ONE FIBERBOARD OVERPACK. THE FIBERBOARD OVERPACK ( with a 19L drum inside ) was placed into a plastic salvage drum. Five of the remaining fiberboard boxes were opend and inspected as this was an unusual type of leakage. Of the five overpacks , 3 of the overpacks had severly dented drums. The shipment was refused and the shipment was picked up by the forwarder on behalf of the shipper.
column169: on the date of the incident 10Feb 2017, Lufthansa ORD contacted our Detroit office requesting disposition and corrective action. One 13Mar the forwarder EMO TRANS was advised of what happended and asked to obtain corrective action from the shipper.   After many reminders from Lufthansa Detroit  the corrective action was never rec'd from the shipper ND Industries from the freight forwarder EMO-TRANS.   Lufthansa ORD notified the ORD FAA Paul Serafin.  FAA Detroit later contact Lufthansa ORD requesting more information.   FAA agent Detroit Craig Nutt contact myself approx. March 6th.   Lufthansa Detroit again contacted by no corrective from the shipper yet.   Lufthansa cargo ORD contacted the shipper ND Industries approx. March 9th   Shipper had corrective and would sent , then 10March follow up , shipper did not yet have corrective action and was given 10 days to provide corrective action from the FAA Detroit ( Craig Nutt    craig.nutt@faa.gov )

The box came into our facility delivered via FedEx truck, but originally flown via air on FedEx Express from New York.  It was identified as an undeclared hazardous material, by our Receiver.  The package has no UN#, no PSN, no orientation labels, no Shippers Declaration.  Regarding the packaging, it was a single walled fiberboard box, no orientation labels, no spec packaging. The inner packaging was bubble wrap, no plastic bag. Inside the box was a smaller box, that contained 2 smaller boxes, which contained 24 each 40ml vials, (960ml),of liquid.  Each vial was in a small ziplock bag. There were 12 vials per smaller box, a small amount of a gray fabric type packing, with nothing in between each vial to prevent breakage. There was a "GLASS FRAGILE" label on the outer box.  The shipment came with an MSDS from 1998, identifying it as UN2986, (which from other vendors with current SDSs, identify it as UN2987).  The Receiver took pictures of the shipment, collected all of the paperwork, (Packing List/certification/Shippers Packing List), and gave it to me.
column169: The Facility "Best Practices" should be updated to include more through Dangerous Goods Shipper Training for anyone shipping any product.  All products considered Dangerous Goods via ground or air should be identified/flagged on the product itself, or at the pull point stocking location, as well as any computer based inventory system.  Specific training for all employees to be able to identify all hazardous material in their facility/stock, as well as General DG awareness and handling. Training to cushion all products during shipment, (hazmat or not), especially glass vials full of Dangerous Goods.

All appropriate departments notified, tank car isolated. CN response team responded noting shipper's seal intact to the protective housing and manway. column162: DIRECTOR, HAZ MAT FIELD OPS + ER
column168: At approximately 11:51 CST, on 2/12/17 the H-SLABAR9-11 was stopped by loss of air on Main track 2 near Prewitt, NM at MP 114.8.  The Key Train was then inspected as required,  During the inspection the train crew identified the UTLX 640571 to be leaking a small amount of liquid from the Bottom Outlet Valve.  The train was secured and the car isolated until responders arrived.  The BNSF Hazmat Team and contract responders were mobilized from Albuquerque.  Upon arrival, BNSF Hazmat inspected the car and found the TOBOV to have not been fully closed.  The valve was closed and the responders inspected the BOV cap, at this point the leak had stopped.  The cap was also found to be less than tool tight.  Responders tightened the cap with a 36" pipe wrench.  A small amount of low pH areas were found on the ballast and ties with a small amount of surface contamination found on the bottom of the tank car.  Responders neutralized this area and surface to ensure that it was safe.  The car was inspected and released to continue on to destination.
column169: The shipper has been notified regarding the condition of this car.  A review of post loading securement and inspections should be performed by the shipper to ensure that all closures are fully closed and securement caps/plugs etc are tool tight.

column168: On 02/13/2017, at 10:35, personnel in the CSXT Cumberland Yard discovered TCIX 175289 , a  loaded tank car of Sodium Hydroxide Solution, leaking from bottom outlet valve flange. The car was isolated and the shipper Axiall, State of Maryland MDE was notified at 11:14 and the NRC was notified, report # 1170940 at 11:21. CHEMTREC was notified at 11:20 Report #2017-02-13-00068. SPSI, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found a defective bottom outlet valve flange. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper. Contractor personnel secured the released, transferred the car and decontaminated the car and cleaned up spilled material. This incident did require a special switching move. 7.1 is required.     Cause Code: 544  NARRI: 2(5+5+0) x(2+0)=40

column168: Tank car UTLX 200835 was reported releasing product in the railyard from the combination housing.  The BNSF responder reported leak source was at UTLX 200835's sample line inside the combination housing.  The defective sample line was leaking due to a hole on the sample line inside of the tank car.  BNSF responder removed the sample line nipple and placed a pipe plug in its place to mitigate the release.

column168: On 02/17/2017, at 1446 hours, Federal Railroad Administration Hazardous Materials Inspectors informed CSX Transportation personnel, while performing an inspection in the the CSXT Warwick Yard discovered ACFX 220493, a Residue tank car of 1,3 Butadiene, leaking from the protective housing. The car was isolated and the shipper, Emerald Performance Materials,  Ohio EPA, and the National Response Center were notified.  (CHEMTREC Report #2017-02-17-00161). SUNPRO, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the vapor line valve open, and the vapor line valve secondary closure plug less than tool tight resulting in the release of hazardous materials. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, Mr. Andy Kulacz - 330-277-2680. Contractor personnel secured the valve and tightened the secondary closure plug to compliance thus securing the release. As of this report, this subsequent inspection by the Federal Railroad Administration Hazardous Materials Inspectors have found the valve self opening, however the secondary closure plug remains secured with no further release. This incident  did not require a special switching move.     NARRI :   5(4+5+0)x(2+0)=90  Cause: 396

column168: ODFL Tractor Trailer was involved in a motor vehicle accident. Another tractor trailer merged off the shoulder onto the roadway in front of the ODFL tractor trailer. the ODFL driver attempted to move to the left to avoid the rear of the other tractor trailer, but contact was made between the right side of the ODFL trailer and the rear of the other tractor trailer, causing the freight inside the ODFL tractor trailer to be damaged and spill from the trailer.

column168: On February 21, 2017 at approximately 2:00 pm, Heritage Technical Services Driver contacted the Technical Services Manager to respond to a leaking 20 gallon container on Heritage Transport trailer located at JCPenney in West Des Moines, Iowa.  Approximately an hour later, the Technical Services Manager arrived to assist the driver with spill response efforts.  Based on the site assessment, a 20 gallon container has inadvertently shifted in the trailer and leaked approximately 1 gallon of material onto the trailer floor and onto the asphalt pavement underneath.  Heritage representatives neutralized the spilled material with baking soda.  Spill clean-up materials  were placed into a 5 gallon container, labeled and transported back to Heritage Environmental Services in Kansas City, Missouri for proper disposal.     Materials Involved in Incident     The leaking container was identified to be Line 1 of manifest 000803321WAS, UN1789, Waste Hydrochloric Acid, 8, PGII, (D002), ERG#157.  Attachment A provides a copy of the Uniform Hazardous Waste manifest, Land Disposal Restriction notice and internal transportation documents used by Heritage for consignment.  Approximately, 1 gallon (10 pounds) spilled from the container.     Root Cause Analysis and Corrective Actions  The 20 gallon container that shifted in the trailer was not properly secured and the bung was not properly tightened.  Heritage is scheduled to conduct additional training on March 15, 2017 on Proper Load Securement and Proper Container Closure.
column169: Root Cause Analysis and Corrective Actions  The 20 gallon container that shifted in the trailer was not properly secured and the bung was not properly tightened.  Heritage is scheduled to conduct additional training on March 15, 2017 on Proper Load Securement and Proper Container Closure.

column168: CN Mechanical Department employee noted liquid coming from the top of tank car TILX 280652 (L / Xylenes; Class 3; PG III) while conducting inspections at CN Kirk Yard; Gary, Indiana. During repair, ball valve was found to be defective. Car owner contacted for disposition.

column168: While moving freight on the dock a forklift operator hit a drum that was already staged on the dock with another piece of freight he was handling. As a result the drum was slightly punctured which contributed to the unintentional release. Spilled material was cleaned up with absorbent and placed into a recovery container as was the punctured drum.
column169: Forklift operators need to pay attention to their clearances including other freight staged on the dock to help prevent these unintentional releases from occurring.

column168: On 2/28/2017 at approximately 15:30 hours a Schneider Transportation Truck was leaving IMTT's main gate and proceeding down 22nd Street when he noticed that product was leaking out of his tanker compartment.  The driver pulled over and began to investigate.  That is when he discovered his wash out cap on the dome of the trailer had come off and was laying in the dome.  Approximately 10 gallons of Invigorate 3.0 had leaked onto the street.  IMTT's Fire Chief was notified along with City of Bayonne Police and Fire Dept.  US Ecology who is IMTT's OSRO was also contacted to initiate a cleanup operation on the roadway as well as the truck.  It was determined that the driver failed to properly secure the wash out cap.
column169: IMTT contacted the customer of the product that was spilled.  All costs associated with the cleanup will be the customer's responsibility.  The trucking company will be responsible for any corrective action on the part of their drivers.

column168: On February 28, 2017 at 10:22 hours, personnel at CSXT Seneca Yard discovered FOBX 90001, a loaded UN 1038, Ethylene, Refrigerated Liquid tank car to have released product from the "boxed" area of the car. The car was isolated and the Shipper, HB Fuller Co Inc. was notified via CHEMTREC, report 2017-02-28-00080. A CSX Emergency Response contractor (Sunpro) was dispatched to the scene. Upon inspection it was determined the liquid was 1/8 of a turn loose and the turn buckle was not secured to the valve.  As a preventative measure the valve was tightened and the turn buckle was properly applied to the valve which stopped the leak.    This tank car is a DOT 113C120W. Question 26a would not allow me to enter this DOT spec into the system. Photo attached with spec included.     NARRI : 5(5+5+0)x(2+0)=100  Cause code: 119
column169: No additional comments.

column168: ON FEBRUARY 2, 2017 AT APPROXIMATELY 21:16 TWO UPS LOADERS WERE PACKAGED INTO A TRAILER. THEY NOTICED A LARGE FIBERBOARD BOX THAT CAME DOWN A CHUTE AND ONTO THE ROLLERS IN THE TRAILER. THE PACKAGE HAS A STEM STICKING OUT OF THE SIDE OF THE FIBERBOARD BOX. THE STEM THAT WAS COMING OUT OF TE SIDE OF THE PACKAGES STRUCK THE STEEL TRANSITION CHUTE AND SMOKE STARTED COMING OUT OF THE PACKAGE. A SUPERVISOR WHO WAS WORKING NEARBY SAW THE SMOKE COMING OUT OF THE PACKAGE AND GRABBED A FIRE EXTINGUISHER AND PUT THE PACKAGE OUT. IN ORDER TO ENSURE THIS PACKAGE HAS BEEN POUT OUT THE PALATINE ILLINOIS FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED AND RESPONDED. 25 EMPLOYEES IN THIS WORK AREA WERE EVACUATED FROM THIS PART OF THE BUILDING. ONCE THE FIRE WAS OUT, THE PACKAGE WAS TAKEN FOR INSPECTION AND WE FOUND A 22 GALLON STAINLESS STEEL GAS TANK. THERE WAS A SMELL OF GASOLINE COMING OUT OF THE TANK. FOUR OUNCES OF GASOLINE WAS REMOVED FOR THE TANK AND THE PACKAGE WAS SECURED PENDING INSPECTION. THE PALATINE FIRE DEPARTMENT BELIEVES THAT A SPARK FROM THE TANK STEM WAS THE CAUSE OF IGNITION. THEY BELIEVE THAT THIS SPARK IGNITED THE RESIDUAL FUEL THAT WAS NOT PROPERLY PURGED FOR THE TANK.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE UNLOADING, A LEAK WAS DISCOVERED INSIDE THE RRTS, INC. TRAILER. UPON INSPECTION, FIVE 5-GALLON PAILS WERE DISCOVERED DAMAGED. APPARENTLY, THE FREIGHT WAS CRUSHED BY HEAVY FREIGHT IN TRANSIT, WHICH RESULTED IN THE LOSS OF APPROXIMATELY 1/2 GALLON FROM EACH PAIL, TOTALING 2.5 GALLONS RELEASED. FREE PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED INSIDE THE TRAILER, AND DID NOT MIGRATE TO THE GROUND SURFACE OR THREATEN TO IMPACT STATE WATERS. RRTS PERSONNEL PERFORMED THE CLEANUP WITH THE APPLICATION OF ABSORBENT MATERIAL TO THE FREE PRODUCT, WHICH WAS RECOVERED AND CONTAINERIZED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM. THE DAMAGED PAILS WERE ALSO OVERPACKED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM. BOTH RECOVERY DRUMS WERE STAGED IN THE TERMINAL'S OS&D AREA, PENDING DISPOSAL IN ACCORDANCE WITH LOCAL, STATE, AND FEDERAL REGULATIONS. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED.
column169: ROADRUNNER TRANSPORTATION SERVICES, INC. WILL CONTINUE TO TRAIN AND REINFORCE SAFE HANDLING PROCEDURES AND DRIVER SAFETY TO ALL PERSONNEL.

column168: Employee was on 2 lane roadway the traffic merges from 2 lanes to one lane. Employee slowed for traffic and started to slid as conditions were icy and slick. Employee rear ended the first vehicle and then swung around as the trailer started to slid and struck another vehicle with the trailer.
column169: The company has a rollover prevention policy titled slip off stay off with cab posters & training reminders. The idea is to bring the vehicle under control without attempting to radically change the path which can cause liquid load shifting & add to the potential for overturn. after each such accident a committee reviews the investigative facts to determine whether the driver followed company safety practices and whether disciplinary actions are appropriate. Our employees receive recurrent training for defensive driving, proper backing techniques and how to prevent rollovers. Employees must past a driver recertification test every three years.

column168: On bill of lading number 1002922864 shipper reported trailer was leaking at/near internal valve. Shipper unloaded trailer and trailer was returned to carrier terminal, washed and tested and inspected. Trailer passed all tests and inspections and was returned to shipper to load bill of lading 1002922864. Again, trailer leaked under load. Trailer was unloaded and returned to carrier’s terminal washed and inspected. This time trailer was torn down to expose the internal valve and it was discovered that the internal valve was missing 3 bolts on the flange plate. Bolts were replaced and trailer placed back into service without further incident.     Motor carrier inspect all new trailers for same issued. Carrier will contact manufactured and report deficiency to them.
column169: Motor carrier inspect all new trailers for same issued. Carrier will contact manufactured and report deficiency to them.

column168: At approximately 14:45 the driver reported he was parked when he noticed a drip coming from the rear external valve dust cap. The driver immediately placed a bucket under the drip to capture the product. Upon notification the company emergency response coordinator notified the LA state hazmat hotline and dispatched USES Environmental Services to the scene. In addition, another tank was dispatched to the scene in order to transfer the load from the leaking tank to the replacement tank. By approximately 15:30 the replacement tank was in place and the LA state police were on scene. At approximately 16:00 USES was on scene. By approximately 23:00 the load had been successfully transferred from the leaking tank to the replacement tank.
column169: Provide further training in order to increase awareness as it relates to tank inspections and prepping tanks for nitric.

FORKLIFT DRIVER WAS MOVING FREIGHT FROM THE TRAILER #5349 @ROSS EXPRESS SUTTON, MA LOADING DOCK. THE FORKLIFT OPERATOR MISJUDGED THE HEIGHT OF THE FORKS WHEN GOING UNDER A PALLET OF HM DRUMS WITH FORKLIFT FORKS. THIS ACTION CAUSED A FORK TO PUNCTURE A DRUM AND CREATED A HOLE IN THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM. AN AMOUNT OF HM PRODUCT LEAKED OUT IN THE TRAILER AND SOME OUT OF THE BACK OF THE TRAILER. FORKLIFT OPERATOR ACTED QUICKLY AND NOTIFIED HIS IMMEDIATE SUPERVISOR WHO INSTRUCTED FORKLIFT OPERATOR TO MAKE A SPEEDY DRY PRODUCT BERM TO PREVENT PRODUCT FROM RUNNING INTO A DRAIN. BLANKETS WERE LAID DOWN UNDER THE FRONT RIGHT EDGE OF THE TRAILER WHERE PRODUCT WAS LEAKING ONTO THE GROUND OUT OF THE BACK OF THE TRAILER. MORE SPEEDY DRY WAS APPLIED TO ALL NECESSARY AREAS. FREIGHT WAS TAKEN OUT OF THE TRAILER AND PLACED ON CLEAN WOODEN PALLETS. THE SUPERVISOR CHECKED HIS SDS BOOK AND EMERGENCY RESPONSE GUIDEBOOK FOR INSTRUCTIONS. SUPERVISOR DID ATTEMPT TO CONTACT/NOTIFY THE SHIPPER – UNIVAR OF THE PRODUCT ISSUE, AND WAS ABLE TO REVIEW SDS SHEET FOR THE PRODUCT IN QUESTION. THIS EVENT STARTED @8PM. THE COMPANY EMPLOYEES CLEANED UP THE HM RAGS, CONTAMINATED SPEED DRY INTO A CONTAINMENT DRUM. THE TRAILER WAS TAKEN OUT OF SERVICE, UNTIL CLEAN-UP WAS ABLE TO BE COMPLETED. THE PRODUCT THAT SPILLED WAS VERY THIN ALMOST LIKE ALCOHOL OR PAINT THINNER, IT SEEMED TO EVAPORATE QUICKLY AND DID NOT LEAVE A RESIDUE BUT LEFT SOME FUMES. THE TRAILER FLOOR WAS CLEANED AND LARGE DOCK FAN USED TO VENT AND DRY OUT TRAILER. ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE WITH A LOCAL VENDOR DOWN THE STREET FROM THE SUTTON, MA TERMINAL TO TAKE THE CONTAINMENT DRUM AWAY FOR PROPER DISPOSAL. THE COMPANY HIRED TO DISPOSE THE CONTAINMENT DRUM WAS-NEDT, 83 GILMORE DRIVE SUTTON, MA. THE CONTAINMENT DRUM WAS PLACED IN A SECURED AREA UNTIL THE DISPOSAL COMPANY WAS ABLE TO COME TO THE FACILITY TO REMOVE THE CONTAINMENT DRUM WITH PRODUCT STILL IN THE DAMAGED DRUM THE NEXT DAY – 2/28/17.
column169: FORKLIFT OPERATOR HAS BEEN COUNSELED ON THE PROPER USE OF FORKLIFT EQUIPMENT AT OUR COMPANY THROUGH OUR SAFETY AND ACCOUNTABILITY PROGRAM.

column168: A PACKAGE SHIPPED THROUGH THE UPS STORE WITH NO HAZARDOUS MARKINGS WAS LOADED INTO A UPS TRAILER. A LOUD SOUND WAS HEARD COMING FROM THE TRAILER AND THEN A BRIEF PERIOD OF SMOKE (BUT NO FIRE). WHEN THE SMOKE CLEARED, PIECES OF EQUIPMENT FROM THE BOX WERE FOUND IN THE TRAILER, INCLUDING THE REMNANTS OF ONE LITHIUM ION CHLORIDE CELL THAT HAD PASSED THROUGH ANOTHER PACKAGE. UPON INVESTIGATION. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT A DEVICE HAVING CONTAINED TWO LITHIUM THIONYL CHLORIDE BATTERIES WAS SHATTERED AND THE BATTERIES AND BROKEN PARTS OF THE DEVICE EJECTED FROM THE BOX. THE DEVICE WAS LABELED APPTEK MODEL ODALOG TYPE RTX2-H2S-1000. ONE LITHIUM BATTERY HAD EXPLODED AND THE OTHER WAS SCORCHED. THE D-SIZED BATTERIES WERE LABELED EWT ER34615M 3.6V 14500MAH. UPS HAS BEEN UNABLE TO DETERMINE THE REASON FRO THE INCIDENT ( EXPLOSION).,

The estimated duration of the release was 6 1/2 hour to migrate the release the ctmv was unloaded.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. TRACTOR-TANKER UNIT WAS STRUCK BY A VEHICLE, CAUSING THE UNIT TO JACK KNIFE, LOSE CONTROL AND GO INTO A DITCH. AS A RESULT, THE TANKER WAS DAMAGED RESULTING IN THE RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY 5,000 GALLONS INTO THE ROADSIDE DITCH. THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT, POLICE AND DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION RESPONDED TO ASSESS THE SITE. ENVIRONMENTAL RESTORATION, LLC (ERLLC) WAS CONTACTED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP. ERLLC DEPLOYED ABSORBENT BOOM IN THE IMPACTED DITCH LINE AND RECOVERED APPROXIMATELY 375 GALLONS OF LIQUID UTILIZING A VACTOR. SITE EXCAVATION IS PENDING.
column169: SINCE THE RELEASE WAS ACCIDENTAL, NO PLANS CURRENTLY EXIST TO PREVENT RECURRENCE. HOWEVER, BRIDGELAND TERMINALS WILL CONTINUE TO REINFORCE SAFETY GUIDELINES AND HANDLING PROCEDURES TO ALL PERSONNEL.

column168: ON THURSDAY FEB 16, 2017 APPROX 8:00 AM, THE SWITCH CREW WAS SWITCHING OUT A LOADED TURPENTINE RAIL TANKCAR, (GATX 56651), IN PREPARATION FOR SHIPMENT. AS THE CAR WENT NORTH APPROXIMATELY ONE BLOCK, THE SWITCH CREW BRAKEMAN STOPPED THE CAR AS HE NOTICED A SMELL OF TURPENTINE AND THE DRIBBLE OF LIQUID DOWN THE SIDE OF THE RAIL FROM THE MANWAY COVER. UPON THIS DISCOVERY, THE CREW IMMEDIATELY MADE EFFORTS TO PUSH THE CAR BACK TO THE TURPENTINE LOADING STATION TO INVESTIGATE. INSPECTORS FROM THE FRA WERE OBSERVING THIS OPERATION, AND STOPPED THE SWITCH CREW AND CONDUCT A DETAILED INVESTIGATION OF THE INCIDENT AT THAT TIME. IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT MANY OF THE NUTS ON THE ON THE MANWAY COVER WERE NOT TIGHTENED PROPERLY, WHICH ALLOWED LIQUID TO SPLASH OUT OF THE COVER WHEN THE RAIL CAR WAS BEING MOVED. IT IS ESTIMATED THAT 1 PINT OF TURPENTINE WAS SPLASHED ON THE SIDE OF THE RAIL CAR.NO TURPENTINE REACHED THE GROUND.THE LOOSENED BOLTS ON THE COVER WERE TIGHTENED UP BEFORE THE CAR WAS MOVED.
column169: CORRECTIVE ACTIONS INCLUDE:- MODIFY PROCEDURE: WE WILL NOW VERIFY BOLT TIGHTNESS ON TOP OF RAIL CARS TWICE. THE FIRST TIME IS WHEN THE CAR IS FILLED AND SECURED FOR TRANSPORTATION TO THE SCALE, AND THE SECOND TIME PRIOR TO SHIPMENT.- PROVIDE BETTER TOOLS FOR JOB: WE WILL INVESTIGATE OPTIONS FOR REPLACING THE CURRENT WRENCHES USED TO TIGHTEN THE BOLTS ON THE RAIL CAR COVERS. WE HOPE TO FIND AN ALTERNATIVE THAT IS SAFE, NON-SPARKING, AND ABLE TO TIGHT BOLTS MORE SECURELY.

column168: DATE: FRIDAY, FEBRUARY 24, 2017  DRIVER: SHAWN WOMACK    INCIDENT SUMMARY   ON WEDNESDAY, FEBRUARY 22, 2017 AT APPROXIMATELY 2215 HOURS, D&A MCRAE DRIVER SHAWN WOMACK WAS LOADED TRAVELING WESTBOUND ON INTERSTATE 80 WEST OF JEREMY RANCH. SHAWN WAS CLIMBING AT APPROXIMATELY 25 MPH TO THE TOP OF PARLEY’S SUMMIT. AS HE PASSED EXIT 140 HE OBSERVED TRAFFIC CONGESTION IN THE RIGHT LANES OF THE ROADWAY AT THE SUMMIT, APPROXIMATELY 300 -400 FEET IN FRONT OF HIM. SHAWN MADE THE DECISION TO CHANGE LANES TO THE LEFT TO STAY CLEAR OF THE CONGESTION. HE CHECKED HIS LEFT MIRROR TO PREPARE FOR THE LANE CHANGE, LOOKED FORWARD AGAIN TO NOTICE THE LAST TRUCK STOPPED IN THE CONGESTION CLOSER THAN IT SHOULD HAVE BEEN. HE PROCEEDED TO MAKE HIS LANE CHANGE INTO THE CENTER LANE, BUT NOT IN TIME TO AVOID THE OTHER TRUCK HITTING HIM. AS HE WAS PASSING THE TRUCK BEFORE THE COLLISION, SHAWN NOTICED THE TRUCK (AN OVER THE ROAD, 53 FT BOX VAN TRAILER, HAULING EMPTY BOTTLES) WAS MOVING BACKWARDS (HE SAW THE FRONT LEFT WHEEL TURNING BACKWARDS). AS IT WAS ROLLING BACKWARDS ON THE INTERSTATE, THE OTHER TRUCK’S LEFT REAR CORNER OF THE TRAILER STRUCK THE LEAD TRAILER ¾’S OF THE WAY DOWN THE RIGHT-SIDE OF THE CARGO TANK.  THIS RUPTURED THE SECOND COMPARTMENT OF THE TANK. SHAWN STOPPED HIS TRUCK, LOOKED IN THE RIGHT-SIDE MIRROR TO SEE CRUDE OIL “GUSHING” OUT OF THE CARGO TANK. HE THEN NOTICED VEHICLES PASSING ON THE LEFT DRIVING THROUGH THE SPILL OIL. HIS THOUGHTS WENT TO STOPPING OTHER VEHICLES FROM DRIVING THROUGH THE SPILL AND CONTACTING 911. AS HE WAS ON THE PHONE WITH 911 A SMALL CAR HAD DROVE THROUGH THE OIL AND IGNITED IT.    AT THIS POINT, SHAWN MOVED UPHILL AWAY FROM THE SCENE WHILE CONTINUING TO TALK WITH 911. HE LOOKED BACK AT THE SCENE AND TO SHAWN IT APPEARED THE OTHER TRUCK HAD MOVED MAYBE TRIED TO PULL AWAY FROM THE COLLISION BECAUSE THE TRACTOR HAD SLIDE OVER CLOSER TO CARGO TANK AND WAS A LITTLE FARTHER BACK, JUST FORWARD OF THE LEAKING OIL. SHAWN NOTICED A UHP OFFICER ON THE DOWNHILL SLIDE OF THE SCENE AND WALKED DOWN TO CONTACT HIM. SHAWN THEN CONTACTED D&A MCRAE MANAGEMENT. I RECEIVED A CALL AT 2220 HOURS SHAWN EXPLAINING WHAT HAD HAPPENED. CHEVRON ROOSEVELT TERMINAL MANAGER ANNA WILKINS WAS NOTIFIED DIRECTLY AT APPROXIMATELY 2245 HOURS. A RESPONSE WAS ORGANIZED AND MANAGEMENT, ROOSEVELT TERMINAL MANAGER ROD CONRAD, AND GENERAL MANAGER GABE EKKER WERE ON THE SCENE BY 0100 HOURS DUE TO DRIVE TIME AND WEATHER.    WHEN I ARRIVED ON SCENE I CONTACTED THE INCIDENT COMMANDER WHO BRIEFED ME ON THE INCIDENT, TOLD ME THEY WERE STILL SEARCHING FOR THE OTHER DRIVER AND REQUESTED I ORGANIZE THE REMOVAL AND REMEDIATION EFFORTS OF OUR VEHICLE. I DID SO, WE HAD A TRUCK TO PUMP OFF THE REMAINING LOAD, ENVIRO-CARE FOR ANY REMEDIATION EFFORTS AND BULLOCKS TOWING ON SCENE WITHIN AN HOUR AND A HALF. ONCE THE SCENE WAS CLEARED, THE REMAINING LOAD WAS TRANSFERRED TO THE AWAITING D&A TRUCK AND DELIVERED TO THE REFINERY THAT MORNING. BULLOCKS TOWING REMOVED OUR VEHICLES AFTER A DOT INSPE
column169: SOLUTION  SHAWN WAS DRIVING THE VEHICLE HE WAS RESPONSIBLE FOR IN A PROFESSIONAL MANNER AND WAS UNFORTUNATELY IN THE WRONG PLACE AT THE WRONG TIME.  WE WILL SHARE THIS INCIDENT WITH OUR DRIVERS AT NEXT WEEK’S SAFETY MEETINGS. WE WILL EMPHASIZE EVEN WHEN YOU ARE FOCUSED, PERFORMING YOUR JOB AT 100% INCIDENTS LIKE THIS CAN HAPPEN. HOW MUCH DO WE INCREASE THE CHANCE OF BEING INVOLVED IN AN INCIDENT WHEN WE ARE GOING 90% OR EVEN 99% FOCUSED?? WE WILL CONTINUE TO FOCUS ON DEFENSIVE DRIVING AND EMERGENCY INCIDENT TRAINING TO DO EVERYTHING WE CAN TO AVOID THESE TYPES OF INCIDENTS AND TRAIN OURSELVES IN THE ACTIONS TO TAKE WHEN THEY UNFORTUNATELY DO OCCUR.     RON CONRAD  TERMINAL MANAGER - ROOSEVELT

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 5 P.M. ON FEBRUARY 8, 2017, DAN SCHAFER CONTACTED ME BY TELEPHONE TO REPORT THAT WE HAD A SPILL THAT MAY HAVE ENTERED A CREEK. DAN DID NOT KNOW HOW MUCH PRODUCT WAS SPILLED, BUT SAID THAT TIM LOVE WAS ON HIS WAY TO THE SITE. DAN SAID THAT A FLEET FUELER HAD A HOSE RUPTURE AT A CUSTOMER SITE.  I THEN CONTACTED TIM LOVE, WHO WAS DRIVING TO THE SITE. I ASKED THAT TIM CONTACT ME IMMEDIATELY AFTER ASSESSING THE EXTENT OF THE RELEASE AND WHETHER THE RELEASE HAD IN FACT ENTERED A WATER WAY.   I THEN CONTACTED COREY MCCORT TO LET HIM KNOW THAT WE HAD A SPILL AND THAT I WAS GATHERING FACTS. I SPOKE WITH LANCE ON SEVERAL OCCASIONS AND COREY TO UPDATE THEM THROUGH THE PROCESS.  TIM THEN ARRIVED AND TOLD ME THAT ADDRESS OF THE SITE IS 7824 N. LEADBETTER. TIM SAID THAT PRODUCT HAD ENTERED A WATER WAY. HE COULD NOT TELL HOW MUCH PRODUCT HAD SPILLED. THE PRODUCT IS ON-ROAD DIESEL. TIM SAID THAT THE CLEANUP IS TOO MUCH FOR US TO HANDLE AND THAT WE NEED HELP.   I THEN INITIATED NOTIFICATION PROCURED AS SET FORTH IN THE CARSON HAZARDOUS MATERIALS RESPONSE PLAN AS FOLLOWS:  1. I CONTACTED NRC TO ASSIST WITH THE CLEAN UP AT 800.283.1150. JASON MITTENBERGER (503.849.1828) SAID THAT HE WOULD GET A CREW TOGETHER AND GET TO THE SITE IMMEDIATELY. I GAVE JASON TIME LOVE’S CELL PHONE NUMBER AND TOLD JASON THAT TIM IS AT THE SITE. JASON SAID HE WOULD ASSESS THE SITUATION AND GET BACK WITH ME.   2. I THEN CONTACTED NRC TO REPORT. IT WAS ABOUT 6:05 P.M. 800.424.8802. I EXPLAINED WHAT HAPPENED AND ALSO SAID THAT IT WAS AN UNDETERMINED AMOUNT OF PRODUCT. NRC ASSIGNED REFERENCE NUMBER 1170596. I SPOKE WITH JUSTIN.   3. I THEN CONTACTED DEQ 800.452.0311 AND NOTIFIED DEQ OF THE RELEASE. DEQ ASSIGNED ORS NUMBER 2017-0511. I SPOKE WITH KEVIN.   4. THE COAST GUARD THEN CONTACTED ME AND I EXPLAINED THE SITUATION. THE COAST GUARD WANTED THE CONTACT INFORMATION FOR SOMEONE AT THE SCENE SO I PROVIDED THEM WITH TIM LOVE’S CELL PHONE NUMBER.   5. THE WASHINGTON DEPT. OF ECOLOGY THEN CALLED, 360.561.9989. I SPOKE WITH MIRIAN DUERR AND EXPLAINED THE SITUATION. SHE SAID THAT WE NEED TO CONTACT HER AND INFORM HER IF THE RELEASE REACHES THE COLUMBIA RIVER.   6. ANGIE OF EPA THEN CALLED, 206.304.8829. I EXPLAINED THE SITUATION TO ANGIE. ANGIE WANTED A CALL BACK WHEN WE KNOW HOW MANY RESPONDERS ARE ON SITE AND WHAT THE CLEANUP IS.   7. AT 7:15 P.M., JASON OF NRC CONTACTED ME. HE SAID THAT HE IS ON THE WAY TO THE SITE AND THAT HE SPOKE WITH EPA AND THE COAST GUARD AND THAT THEY WANTED US TO BOOM THE MOUTH OF THE COLUMBIA SLOUGH. HE ALSO SAID THAT HE DEPLOYED 4 PEOPLE ON LAND AND HAS A VAC TRUCK ON STANDBY IN CASE WE NEED IT.   8. JASON THEN CALLED BACK AT 7:25 P.M. AND REPORTED THAT THE PRODUCT HAD ENTERED A BIO-SWALE ADJACENT TO THE PROPERTY. WHILE THE BIO-SWALE HAS AN OUTFALL, THE GROUND IS DRY FROM AT LEAST 100 BEFORE THE OUTFALL AND THUS THE PRODUCT IS COMPLETELY CONTAINED.   9. AT 8 P.M. TIM LOVE CALLED AND SAID HE TURNED THE PROJECT OVER TO NRC.  10. AT 8:15 P.M., I CALLED A

column168: WHEN THE DRIVER ARRIVED TO MAKE HIS DELIVERY HE LOOKED AT THE PLASTIC TUBE CONNECTED TO THE TANK WHICH WOULD SHOW THE LEVEL OF DIESEL CONTAINED IN THE TANK. THE PROBLEM HE ENCOUNTERED WAS THAT THE TUBE WAS SO FADED FROM THE DIESEL IN IT PLUS SUN DAMAGE HE COULDN’T SEE THE LEVEL OF THE DIESEL IN THE TANK. AT THAT POINT HE LOOKED AT A METER GAUGE WHICH HAD BEEN INSTALLED ON THE TANK AS WELL AND HE WAS ABLE TO GET A LEVEL READING OFF OF IT. AT THIS POINT BASED ON THE LEVEL READING THE DIESEL HE WAS GOING TO DELIVER WOULD FIT IN THE TANK. HE PROCEEDED TO UNLOAD AND JUST PRIOR TO HIM BEING FINISHED THE TANK OVERFILLED SPILLING APPROXIMATELY 10 GALLONS OF DIESEL IN THE CONCRETE CONTAINMENT WALL OF THE STORAGE TANK. HE LOOKED BACK AT THE METER ON THE SIDE OF TANK TO FIND OUT THAT IT WASN’T WORKING PROPERLY AS WELL. HE IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED HIS SAFETY SUPERVISOR AND THEY CAME TO THE SITE AND CLEANED THE SPILLED THAT WAS IN THE CONTAINMENT WALL.
column169: THE CUSTOMER WAS NOTIFIED OF THE SPILL AND A REPORT WAS DONE TO DETERMINED A SOLUTION TO CORRECT THE ISSUE. IT WAS DECIDED THAT OUR MAINTENANCE DEPARTMENT WOULD REPLACE THE CUSTOMERS PLASTIC FILL TUBE WHICH WAS FADED AND NO LONGER COULD SEE THE DIESEL IN THE LINE. WE ALSO HAD THE TANK METER CHECKED AND REPAIRED. WE ALSO MADE OUR TANK WAGON DRIVERS OF THE SITUATION AND ALSO TOLD THEM IN A MEMO THAT THIS TANK IS NOT TO BE FILLED PAST THE 9000 GALLON LEVEL.

column168: On February 26th, EQ Northeast, Inc. picked up a loaded roll-off container at Global Foundaries at 400 Stone Break Road in Malta NY. The container was tarped, properly loaded and secured to the roll-off trailer, and transported to Veolia Technical Solutions 10 day facility in Schenectady NY, where it was to be placed into 10 day storage.     As the driver was transferring the can from the roll-off trailer to the ground, the load shifted and slid to the back of the container. A NON-RQ amount of material was able to navigate between the roll-off can and the tarp, and onto the ground at Veolia’s facility. The EQ Northeast driver used the contents of his spill kit to quickly clean the waste up and put back into the container. Upon further inspection of the load, it was determined that excessive moisture within the material caused the load to shift.  Further, the container used for transport of this material was not designed for the consistency of the material that was placed in it.
column169: The transporter has two recommendations to prevent future occurrences:     1. The generator needs to ensure this material is properly pressed, removing all free liquids prior to being loaded into the container.      There was a treatment system upset, that coincided with this event, that fouled the press cloths and caused the filter cake condition to contain more moisture than usual.  However, the roll-off was not shipped off site with visible free liquids.    Based on the observations, it is likely that the filter cake contained sufficient moisture that the vibrations of transport caused the liquid to separate after it left the site.    As a result of this investigation, Global Foundries will amend their procedure(s) to have a qualified person inspect the container when there is an observation that the filter cake may contain more moisture than normal and adjust their criteria for intervention to make sure it is explicit that "wet" filter cake is required to be addressed in the same manner as if there was visible free liquid.    2. The material needs to be loaded into de-watering boxes, which allow any free liquids to filter through the load and be pumped out prior to transport.     All roll-off cans associated with this material have already been switched to de-watering boxes as of 3/2/18.
